title: About Me
text:
Hello everyone!


I am Jiayue Ma, currently a graduate student at Weitzman School of Design, University of Pennsylvania, studying for a dual degree in city planning and urban spatial analytics. Before I came to Philadelphia, I completed the 5-year undergraduate program in city planning at Zhejiang University.


As a data enthusiast and urban planner, I’m interested in a wide range of topics, including urban resilience, transportation system, as well as creative urban-design.
I have experience in data analysis, spatial analysis, and data visualization.
I currently work as a research assistant at EMLab at Penn.
If you are interested in reaching out, please contact me through my email: majiayue@design.upenn.edu  This site is an demonstration site of my final project for MUSA 550, during fall 2024.

href: analysis/4-folium.html#finding-the-shortest-route
title: Interactive Maps with Folium
text:
Finding the shortest route
This example finds the shortest route between the Art Musuem and the Liberty Bell using osmnx.

import osmnx as ox

First, identify the lat/lng coordinates for our places of interest. Use osmnx to download the geometries for the Libery Bell and Art Museum.

philly_tourism = ox.features_from_place("Philadelphia, PA", tags={"tourism": True})


art_museum = philly_tourism.query("name == 'Philadelphia Museum of Art'").squeeze()

art_museum.geometry









liberty_bell = philly_tourism.query("name == 'Liberty Bell'").squeeze()

liberty_bell.geometry








Now, extract the lat and lng coordinates
For the Art Museum geometry, we can use the .geometry.centroid attribute to calculate the centroid of the building footprint.

liberty_bell_x = liberty_bell.geometry.x
liberty_bell_y = liberty_bell.geometry.y


art_museum_x = art_museum.geometry.centroid.x
art_museum_y = art_museum.geometry.centroid.y

Next, use osmnx to download the street graph around Center City.

G_cc = ox.graph_from_address(
    "City Hall, Philadelphia, USA", dist=1500, network_type="drive"
)

Next, identify the nodes in the graph closest to our points of interest.

# Get the origin node (Liberty Bell)
orig_node = ox.nearest_nodes(G_cc, liberty_bell_x, liberty_bell_y)

# Get the destination node (Art Musuem)
dest_node = ox.nearest_nodes(G_cc, art_museum_x, art_museum_y)

Find the shortest path, based on the distance of the edges:

# Get the shortest path --> just a list of node IDs
route = ox.shortest_path(G_cc, orig_node, dest_node, weight="length")

How about an interactive version?
osmnx has a helper function ox.utils_graph.route_to_gdf() to convert a route to a GeoDataFrame of edges.

ox.utils_graph.route_to_gdf(G_cc, route, weight="length").explore(
    tiles="cartodb positron",
    color="red",
)

title: Interactive Maps with Folium
text:
Examining Trash-Related 311 Requests
First, let’s load the dataset from a CSV file and convert to a GeoDataFrame:


Code
# Load the data from a CSV file into a pandas DataFrame
trash_requests_df = pd.read_csv(
    "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MUSA-550-Fall-2023/week-4/main/data/trash_311_requests_2020.csv"
)

# Remove rows with missing geometry
trash_requests_df = trash_requests_df.dropna(subset=["lat", "lon"])


# Create our GeoDataFrame with geometry column created from lon/lat
trash_requests = gpd.GeoDataFrame(
    trash_requests_df,
    geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(trash_requests_df["lon"], trash_requests_df["lat"]),
    crs="EPSG:4326",
)


Load neighborhoods and do the spatial join to associate a neighborhood with each ticket:


Code
# Load the neighborhoods
neighborhoods = gpd.read_file(
    "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MUSA-550-Fall-2023/week-4/main/data/zillow_neighborhoods.geojson"
)

# Do the spatial join to add the "ZillowName" column
requests_with_hood = gpd.sjoin(
    trash_requests,
    neighborhoods.to_crs(trash_requests.crs),
    predicate="within",
)


Let’s explore the 311 requests in the Greenwich neighborhood of the city:

# Extract out the point tickets for Greenwich
greenwich_tickets = requests_with_hood.query("ZillowName == 'Greenwich'")


# Get the neighborhood boundary for Greenwich
greenwich_geo = neighborhoods.query("ZillowName == 'Greenwich'")

greenwich_geo.squeeze().geometry














Note



Quarto has callout blocks that you can use to emphasize content in different ways. This is a “Note” callout block. More info is available on the Quarto documentation.


Import the packages we need:

import folium
import xyzservices

Combine the tickets as markers and the neighborhood boundary on the same Folium map:

# Plot the neighborhood boundary
m = greenwich_geo.explore(
    style_kwds={"weight": 4, "color": "black", "fillColor": "none"},
    name="Neighborhood boundary",
    tiles=xyzservices.providers.CartoDB.Voyager,
)


# Add the individual tickets as circle markers and style them
greenwich_tickets.explore(
    m=m,  # Add to the existing map!
    marker_kwds={"radius": 7, "fill": True, "color": "crimson"},
    marker_type="circle_marker", # or 'marker' or 'circle'
    name="Tickets",
)

# Hse folium to add layer control
folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)

m  # show map

# Make the heatmap with hvplot
heatmap = measles.hvplot.heatmap(
    x="YEAR",
    y="state",
    C="incidence", # color each square by the incidence
    reduce_function=np.sum, # sum the incidence for each state/year
    frame_height=450,
    frame_width=600,
    flip_yaxis=True,
    rot=90,
    colorbar=False,
    cmap="viridis",
    xlabel="",
    ylabel="",
)

# Some additional formatting using holoviews 
# For more info: http://holoviews.org/user_guide/Customizing_Plots.html
heatmap = heatmap.redim(state="State", YEAR="Year")
heatmap = heatmap.opts(fontsize={"xticks": 0, "yticks": 6}, toolbar="above")
heatmap

title: Showing static visualizations
text:
A simple visualization, 3 different ways

I want to scatter flipper length vs. bill length, colored by the penguin species


Using matplotlib

# Setup a dict to hold colors for each species
color_map = {"Adelie": "#1f77b4", "Gentoo": "#ff7f0e", "Chinstrap": "#D62728"}

# Initialize the figure "fig" and axes "ax"
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# Group the data frame by species and loop over each group
# NOTE: "group" will be the dataframe holding the data for "species"
for species, group_df in penguins.groupby("species"):

    # Plot flipper length vs bill length for this group
    # Note: we are adding this plot to the existing "ax" object
    ax.scatter(
        group_df["flipper_length_mm"],
        group_df["bill_length_mm"],
        marker="o",
        label=species,
        color=color_map[species],
        alpha=0.75,
        zorder=10
    )

# Plotting is done...format the axes!

## Add a legend to the axes
ax.legend(loc="best")

## Add x-axis and y-axis labels
ax.set_xlabel("Flipper Length (mm)")
ax.set_ylabel("Bill Length (mm)")

## Add the grid of lines
ax.grid(True);










How about in pandas?
DataFrames have a built-in “plot” function that can make all of the basic type of matplotlib plots!
First, we need to add a new “color” column specifying the color to use for each species type.
Use the pd.replace() function: it use a dict to replace values in a DataFrame column.

# Calculate a list of colors
color_map = {"Adelie": "#1f77b4", "Gentoo": "#ff7f0e", "Chinstrap": "#D62728"}

# Map species name to color 
penguins["color"] = penguins["species"].replace(color_map)

    x="flipper_length_mm",
    y="bill_length_mm",
    c="color",
    alpha=0.75,
    ax=myAxes, # IMPORTANT: Make sure to plot on the axes object we created already!
    zorder=10
)

# Format the axes finally
myAxes.set_xlabel("Flipper Length (mm)")
myAxes.set_ylabel("Bill Length (mm)")
myAxes.grid(True);








Note: no easy way to get legend added to the plot in this case…


Seaborn: statistical data visualization
Seaborn is designed to plot two columns colored by a third column…

# Initialize the figure and axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# style keywords as dict
color_map = {"Adelie": "#1f77b4", "Gentoo": "#ff7f0e", "Chinstrap": "#D62728"}
style = dict(palette=color_map, s=60, edgecolor="none", alpha=0.75, zorder=10)

# use the scatterplot() function
sns.scatterplot(
    x="flipper_length_mm",  # the x column
    y="bill_length_mm",  # the y column
    hue="species",  # the third dimension (color)
    data=penguins,  # pass in the data
    ax=ax,  # plot on the axes object we made
    **style  # add our style keywords
)

# Format with matplotlib commands
ax.set_xlabel("Flipper Length (mm)")
ax.set_ylabel("Bill Length (mm)")
ax.grid(True)
ax.legend(loc="best");

title: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation with Pix2Pix
text:
This research explores the application of a Pix2Pix Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) model to translate from land cover maps to satellite imagery. By the use of 1,000 paired datasets sourced from diverse land cover types, the project aims to train a conditional GAN capable of producing realistic satellite images from land cover data.
The study is meaningful as it provides a method for visualizing landscape changes and potential future developments. Such a tool can simulate and assess the impact of urbanization, land-use planning, or ecological shifts by generating predictive satellite imagery based on hypothetical scenarios. The integration of machine learning and geospatial data provides a useful tool in environmental planning, offering a scalable solution for decision-makers.

Generating Random Locations Within Study Area

def generate_random_points_all(polygon1, polygon2, total_num_points):
    def generate_points(polygon, num_points):
        minx, miny, maxx, maxy = polygon.bounds
        points = []
        attempts = 0
        max_attempts = num_points * 10  
        while len(points) < num_points and attempts < max_attempts:
            random_point = Point(random.uniform(minx, maxx), random.uniform(miny, maxy))
            if polygon.contains(random_point):
                points.append({'latitude': random_point.y, 'longitude': random_point.x})
            attempts += 1
        return points
    
    num_points_per_polygon = total_num_points * 0.9

    points1 = generate_points(polygon1, num_points_per_polygon)
    points2 = generate_points(polygon2, total_num_points - num_points_per_polygon)  

    return points1 + points2


if os.path.exists(coords):
    with open(coords, 'r') as f:
        coords_points = json.load(f)
    print(f"Loaded {len(coords_points)} coordinates from {coords}")
else:
    num_points = 1000
    coords_points = generate_random_points_all(aoi1_geometry, aoi2_geometry, num_points)
    with open(coords, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(coords_points, f)
    print(f"Generated and saved {len(coords_points)} coordinates to {coords}")

Fetching Real Color and Land Cover Images Through Google Earth Engine

true_color_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/RC'
land_cover_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/LC'
os.makedirs(true_color_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(land_cover_dir, exist_ok=True)

def process_point(idx, coord):
    lat = coord['latitude']
    lon = coord['longitude']
    point = ee.Geometry.Point(lon, lat)
    print(lat, lon)

    img_size = 1024
    pixel_scale = 10 
    buffer_size = (img_size / 2) * pixel_scale  
    region = point.buffer(buffer_size).bounds()

    collection = ee.ImageCollection('LANDSAT/LC08/C02/T1_TOA') \
        .filterBounds(point) \
        .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-12-31') \
        .sort('CLOUD_COVER') \
        .limit(1)

    image = collection.first()
    if image is None:
        print(f"No true-color image found for point {idx+1}")
    else:
        image_rgb = image.select(['B4', 'B3', 'B2'])
        vis_params_rgb = {
            'min': 0,
            'max': 0.3,
        }

        thumbnail_rgb = image_rgb.getThumbURL({
            'region': region,
            'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
            'format': 'png',
            'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
            'min': vis_params_rgb['min'],
            'max': vis_params_rgb['max'],
        })

        response_rgb = requests.get(thumbnail_rgb)
        if response_rgb.status_code == 200:
            image_path_rgb = os.path.join(true_color_dir, f'image_{idx}.png')
            with open(image_path_rgb, 'wb') as f:
                f.write(response_rgb.content)
            print(f"Downloaded true-color image {idx+1}/{len(coords_points)} to {image_path_rgb}")
        else:
            print(f"Failed to download true-color image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_rgb.status_code}")

    landcover = ee.Image('ESA/WorldCover/v100/2020')

    image_lc = landcover.clip(region)

    vis_params_lc = {
        'min': 10,
        'max': 100,
        'palette': [
            '006400',  # Tree cover (10): Dark Green
            'ffbb22',  # Shrubland (20): Orange
            'ffff4c',  # Grassland (30): Yellow
            'f096ff',  # Cropland (40): Pink
            'fa0000',  # Built-up (50): Red
            'b4b4b4',  # Bare/sparse vegetation (60): Grey
            'f0f0f0',  # Snow and ice (70): White
            '0064c8',  # Permanent water bodies (80): Blue
            '0096a0',  # Herbaceous wetland (90): Teal
            '00cf75',  # Mangroves (95): Light Green
            'fae6a0',  # Moss and lichen (100): Beige
        ]
    }

    thumbnail_lc = image_lc.getThumbURL({
        'region': region,
        'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
        'format': 'png',
        'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
        'min': vis_params_lc['min'],
        'max': vis_params_lc['max'],
        'palette': vis_params_lc['palette'],
    })

    response_lc = requests.get(thumbnail_lc)
    if response_lc.status_code == 200:
        image_path_lc = os.path.join(land_cover_dir, f'image_{idx}.png')
        with open(image_path_lc, 'wb') as f:
            f.write(response_lc.content)
        print(f"Downloaded land cover image {idx+1}/{len(coords_points)} to {image_path_lc}")
    else:
        print(f"Failed to download land cover image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_lc.status_code}")

for idx, coord in enumerate(coords_points):
    try:
        process_point(idx, coord)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred at point {idx+1}: {e}")
        continue

Transform Training Data

lc_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/LC'
tc_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/RC'
training_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/training'
val_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/validation'
test_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/test'

os.makedirs(training_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(val_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(test_dir, exist_ok=True)

all_filenames = [f for f in os.listdir(lc_dir) if f.endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg'))]
np.random.shuffle(all_filenames)  

num_images = len(all_filenames)
num_val = int(num_images * 0.1)
num_test = int(num_images * 0.1)

val_filenames = all_filenames[:num_val]
test_filenames = all_filenames[num_val:num_val + num_test]
train_filenames = all_filenames[num_val + num_test:]

def process_and_save_images(filenames, target_dir):
    for filename in filenames:
        lc_path = os.path.join(lc_dir, filename)
        tc_name = filename.replace('_pillow', '')  
        tc_path = os.path.join(tc_dir, tc_name)

        if os.path.exists(tc_path):
            lc_image = Image.open(lc_path).resize((256, 256))
            tc_image = Image.open(tc_path).resize((256, 256))

            combined_image = Image.new('RGB', (512, 256))  
            combined_image.paste(lc_image, (0, 0))
            combined_image.paste(tc_image, (256, 0))

            output_path = os.path.join(target_dir, tc_name)
            combined_image.save(output_path)

            print(f'Saved combined image: {output_path}')
        else:
            print(f'Image not found for: {tc_name}')

process_and_save_images(val_filenames, val_dir)
process_and_save_images(test_filenames, test_dir)
process_and_save_images(train_filenames, training_dir)

def load(image_file):
    # Read and decode an image file to a uint8 tensor
    image = tf.io.read_file(image_file)
    image = tf.io.decode_jpeg(image)

    # Split each image tensor into two tensors:
    # - one with a real color satellite image
    # - one with a land cover image 
    w = tf.shape(image)[1]
    w = w // 2
    input_image = image[:, :w, :]
    real_image = image[:, w:, :]

    # Convert both images to float32 tensors
    input_image = tf.cast(input_image, tf.float32)
    real_image = tf.cast(real_image, tf.float32)

    return input_image, real_image

# The satellite training set consist of 1000 images
BUFFER_SIZE = 1000
# The batch size of 1 produced better results for the U-Net in the original pix2pix experiment
BATCH_SIZE = 1
# Each image is 256x256 in size
IMG_WIDTH = 256
IMG_HEIGHT = 256

def resize(input_image, real_image, height, width):
    input_image = tf.image.resize(input_image, [height, width],
                                method=tf.image.ResizeMethod.NEAREST_NEIGHBOR)
    real_image = tf.image.resize(real_image, [height, width],
                               method=tf.image.ResizeMethod.NEAREST_NEIGHBOR)

    return input_image, real_image


def random_crop(input_image, real_image):
    stacked_image = tf.stack([input_image, real_image], axis=0)
    cropped_image = tf.image.random_crop(
      stacked_image, size=[2, IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3])

    return cropped_image[0], cropped_image[1]

# Normalizing the images to [-1, 1]
def normalize(input_image, real_image):
    input_image = (input_image / 127.5) - 1
    real_image = (real_image / 127.5) - 1

    return input_image, real_image

@tf.function()
def random_jitter(input_image, real_image):
    # Resizing to 286x286
    input_image, real_image = resize(input_image, real_image, 286, 286)

    # Random cropping back to 256x256
    input_image, real_image = random_crop(input_image, real_image)

    if tf.random.uniform(()) > 0.5:
        # Random mirroring
        input_image = tf.image.flip_left_right(input_image)
        real_image = tf.image.flip_left_right(real_image)

    return input_image, real_image

OUTPUT_CHANNELS = 3

def downsample(filters, size, apply_batchnorm=True):
  initializer = tf.random_normal_initializer(0., 0.02)

  result = tf.keras.Sequential()
  result.add(
      tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters, size, strides=2, padding='same',
                             kernel_initializer=initializer, use_bias=False))

  if apply_batchnorm:
    result.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())

  result.add(tf.keras.layers.LeakyReLU())

  return result

def upsample(filters, size, apply_dropout=False):
  initializer = tf.random_normal_initializer(0., 0.02)

  result = tf.keras.Sequential()
  result.add(
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters, size, strides=2,
                                    padding='same',
                                    kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                    use_bias=False))

  result.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())

  if apply_dropout:
      result.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5))

  result.add(tf.keras.layers.ReLU())

  return result

def Generator():
  inputs = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=[256, 256, 3])

  down_stack = [
    downsample(64, 4, apply_batchnorm=False),  # (batch_size, 128, 128, 64)
    downsample(128, 4),  # (batch_size, 64, 64, 128)
    downsample(256, 4),  # (batch_size, 32, 32, 256)
    downsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 16, 16, 512)
    downsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 8, 8, 512)
    downsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 4, 4, 512)
    downsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 2, 2, 512)
    downsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 1, 1, 512)
  ]

  up_stack = [
    upsample(512, 4, apply_dropout=True),  # (batch_size, 2, 2, 1024)
    upsample(512, 4, apply_dropout=True),  # (batch_size, 4, 4, 1024)
    upsample(512, 4, apply_dropout=True),  # (batch_size, 8, 8, 1024)
    upsample(512, 4),  # (batch_size, 16, 16, 1024)
    upsample(256, 4),  # (batch_size, 32, 32, 512)
    upsample(128, 4),  # (batch_size, 64, 64, 256)
    upsample(64, 4),  # (batch_size, 128, 128, 128)
  ]

  initializer = tf.random_normal_initializer(0., 0.02)
  last = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(OUTPUT_CHANNELS, 4,
                                         strides=2,
                                         padding='same',
                                         kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                         activation='tanh')  # (batch_size, 256, 256, 3)

  x = inputs

  # Downsampling through the model
  skips = []
  for down in down_stack:
    x = down(x)
    skips.append(x)

  skips = reversed(skips[:-1])

  # Upsampling and establishing the skip connections
  for up, skip in zip(up_stack, skips):
    x = up(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Concatenate()([x, skip])

  x = last(x)

  return tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=x)


generator = Generator()

LAMBDA = 100

loss_object = tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True)

def generator_loss(disc_generated_output, gen_output, target):
    gan_loss = loss_object(tf.ones_like(disc_generated_output), disc_generated_output)

    # Mean absolute error
    l1_loss = tf.reduce_mean(tf.abs(target - gen_output))

    total_gen_loss = gan_loss + (LAMBDA * l1_loss)
    
    return total_gen_loss, gan_loss, l1_loss



Building Pix2Pix Model - Discriminator

def Discriminator():
  initializer = tf.random_normal_initializer(0., 0.02)

  inp = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=[256, 256, 3], name='input_image')
  tar = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=[256, 256, 3], name='target_image')

  x = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([inp, tar])  # (batch_size, 256, 256, channels*2)

  down1 = downsample(64, 4, False)(x)  # (batch_size, 128, 128, 64)
  down2 = downsample(128, 4)(down1)  # (batch_size, 64, 64, 128)
  down3 = downsample(256, 4)(down2)  # (batch_size, 32, 32, 256)

  zero_pad1 = tf.keras.layers.ZeroPadding2D()(down3)  # (batch_size, 34, 34, 256)
  conv = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(512, 4, strides=1,
                                kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                use_bias=False)(zero_pad1)  # (batch_size, 31, 31, 512)

  batchnorm1 = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(conv)

  leaky_relu = tf.keras.layers.LeakyReLU()(batchnorm1)

  zero_pad2 = tf.keras.layers.ZeroPadding2D()(leaky_relu)  # (batch_size, 33, 33, 512)

  last = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(1, 4, strides=1,
                                kernel_initializer=initializer)(zero_pad2)  # (batch_size, 30, 30, 1)

  return tf.keras.Model(inputs=[inp, tar], outputs=last)


discriminator = Discriminator()
tf.keras.utils.plot_model(discriminator, show_shapes=True, dpi=64)









def discriminator_loss(disc_real_output, disc_generated_output):
    real_loss = loss_object(tf.ones_like(disc_real_output), disc_real_output)

    generated_loss = loss_object(tf.zeros_like(disc_generated_output), disc_generated_output)

    total_disc_loss = real_loss + generated_loss
    
    return total_disc_loss

Building Pix2Pix Model - Generating Images

def generate_images(model, test_input, tar, save_dir, prefix='image', max_images=100):
    os.makedirs(save_dir, exist_ok=True)
    
    test_input = tf.squeeze(test_input, axis=1)
    tar = tf.squeeze(tar, axis=1)

    predictions = model(test_input, training=True)

    num_images = min(test_input.shape[0], max_images)

    for i in range(num_images):
        plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

        display_list = [test_input[i], tar[i], predictions[i]]
        title = ['Input Image', 'Ground Truth', 'Predicted Image']

        for j in range(3):
            plt.subplot(1, 3, j+1)
            plt.title(title[j])
            plt.imshow(display_list[j] * 0.5 + 0.5)
            plt.axis('off')

        image_path = os.path.join(save_dir, f'{prefix}_{i}.png')
        plt.savefig(image_path)
        plt.close()

log_dir = './24-1204_Pix2Pix_3/logs/'

summary_writer = tf.summary.create_file_writer(
  log_dir + "fit/" + datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"))


gen_gan_loss_list = []
gen_l1_loss_list = []
gen_total_loss_list = []
disc_loss_list = []
data = 0
@tf.function
def train_step(input_image, target):
    with tf.GradientTape() as gen_tape, tf.GradientTape() as disc_tape:
        gen_output = generator(input_image, training=True)

        disc_real_output = discriminator([input_image, target], training=True)
        disc_generated_output = discriminator([input_image, gen_output], training=True)

        gen_total_loss, gen_gan_loss, gen_l1_loss = generator_loss(
            disc_generated_output, gen_output, target)
        disc_loss = discriminator_loss(disc_real_output, disc_generated_output)

    generator_gradients = gen_tape.gradient(gen_total_loss, generator.trainable_variables)
    discriminator_gradients = disc_tape.gradient(disc_loss, discriminator.trainable_variables)

    generator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(generator_gradients, generator.trainable_variables))
    discriminator_optimizer.apply_gradients(zip(discriminator_gradients, discriminator.trainable_variables))

    with summary_writer.as_default():
        tf.summary.scalar('gen_total_loss', gen_total_loss, step=step)
        tf.summary.scalar('gen_gan_loss', gen_gan_loss, step=step)
        tf.summary.scalar('gen_l1_loss', gen_l1_loss, step=step)
        tf.summary.scalar('disc_loss', disc_loss, step=step)

    return gen_total_loss, gen_gan_loss, gen_l1_loss, disc_loss


def fit(train_ds, test_ds, steps):
    from builtins import enumerate  
    example_input, example_target = next(iter(test_ds.batch(45).take(1)))
    start = time.time()

    for step, (input_image, target) in enumerate(train_ds.repeat().take(steps)):
        gen_total_loss, gen_gan_loss, gen_l1_loss, disc_loss = train_step(input_image, target)

        if step % 1000 == 0:
            if step != 0:
                print(f'\nTime taken for 1000 steps: {time.time() - start:.2f} sec\n')
                # Print the losses
                print('Discriminator loss:', disc_loss.numpy())
                print('Generator GAN loss:', gen_gan_loss.numpy())
                print('Generator L1 loss:', gen_l1_loss.numpy())
                print('Generator total loss:', gen_total_loss.numpy())
            start = time.time()

            save_dir = './24-1204_Pix2Pix_3/generated_images' 
            generate_images(generator, example_input, example_target, save_dir, prefix=f'step_{step}')
            print(f"Step: {step // 1000}k")

        if (step + 1) % 10 == 0:
            print('.', end='', flush=True)

        try:
            if (step + 1) % 5000 == 0:
                checkpoint.save(file_prefix=checkpoint_prefix)
        except UnicodeDecodeError as e:
            print(f"Checkpoint save error: {e}")

        #with summary_writer.as_default():
            #tf.summary.scalar('gen_total_loss', gen_total_loss, step=step)

true_color_dir_test = './24-1204_training_images_2/RC_test'
land_cover_dir_test = './24-1204_training_images_2/LC_test'
os.makedirs(true_color_dir_test, exist_ok=True)

def process_point_test(idx, coord):
    lat = coord['latitude']
    lon = coord['longitude']
    point = ee.Geometry.Point(lon, lat)
    print(lat, lon)

    img_size = 1024
    pixel_scale = 10 
    buffer_size = (img_size / 2) * pixel_scale  
    region = point.buffer(buffer_size).bounds()

    collection = ee.ImageCollection('LANDSAT/LC08/C02/T1_TOA') \
        .filterBounds(point) \
        .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-12-31') \
        .sort('CLOUD_COVER') \
        .limit(1)

    image = collection.first()
    if image is None:
        print(f"No true-color image found for point {idx+1}")
    else:
        image_rgb = image.select(['B4', 'B3', 'B2'])
        vis_params_rgb = {
            'min': 0,
            'max': 0.3,
        }

        thumbnail_rgb = image_rgb.getThumbURL({
            'region': region,
            'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
            'format': 'png',
            'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
            'min': vis_params_rgb['min'],
            'max': vis_params_rgb['max'],
        })

        response_rgb = requests.get(thumbnail_rgb)
        if response_rgb.status_code == 200:
            image_path_rgb = os.path.join(true_color_dir_test, f'image_{idx}.png')
            with open(image_path_rgb, 'wb') as f:
                f.write(response_rgb.content)
            print(f"Downloaded true-color image {idx+1}/{len(coords_test_points)} to {image_path_rgb}")
        else:
            print(f"Failed to download true-color image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_rgb.status_code}")

    landcover = ee.Image('ESA/WorldCover/v100/2020')

    image_lc = landcover.clip(region)

    vis_params_lc = {
        'min': 10,
        'max': 100,
        'palette': [
            '006400',  # Tree cover (10): Dark Green
            'ffbb22',  # Shrubland (20): Orange
            'ffff4c',  # Grassland (30): Yellow
            'f096ff',  # Cropland (40): Pink
            'fa0000',  # Built-up (50): Red
            'b4b4b4',  # Bare/sparse vegetation (60): Grey
            'f0f0f0',  # Snow and ice (70): White
            '0064c8',  # Permanent water bodies (80): Blue
            '0096a0',  # Herbaceous wetland (90): Teal
            '00cf75',  # Mangroves (95): Light Green
            'fae6a0',  # Moss and lichen (100): Beige
        ]
    }

    thumbnail_lc = image_lc.getThumbURL({
        'region': region,
        'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
        'format': 'png',
        'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
        'min': vis_params_lc['min'],
        'max': vis_params_lc['max'],
        'palette': vis_params_lc['palette'],
    })

    response_lc = requests.get(thumbnail_lc)
    if response_lc.status_code == 200:
        image_path_lc = os.path.join(land_cover_dir_test, f'image_{idx}.png')
        with open(image_path_lc, 'wb') as f:
            f.write(response_lc.content)
        print(f"Downloaded land cover image {idx+1}/{len(coords_test_points)} to {image_path_lc}")
    else:
        print(f"Failed to download land cover image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_lc.status_code}")

for idx, coord in enumerate(coords_test_points):
    try:
        process_point_test(idx, coord)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred at point {idx+1}: {e}")
        continue

os.makedirs(test_generation_path, exist_ok=True)

def preprocess_image(image_path):
    image = Image.open(image_path)
    image = image.resize((256, 256))
    image = np.array(image)
    image = (image / 127.5) - 1.0  
    image = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)
    return image

def generate_image(model, test_lc_input, ground_truth, save_path):
    generated_lc_test = model(test_lc_input, training=True)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    display_list = [test_lc_input[0], generated_lc_test[0], ground_truth[0]]
    titles = ['Test LC', 'Generated RC', 'Ground Truth']

    for i in range(3):
        plt.subplot(1, 3, i+1)
        plt.title(titles[i])
        plt.imshow((display_list[i] * 0.5) + 0.5)
        plt.axis('off')

    plt.savefig(save_path)
    plt.close()
    print(f'Saved composite image: {save_path}')

for image_file in os.listdir(test_lc_path):
    if image_file.endswith('.jpg') or image_file.endswith('.png'):
        test_lc_image_path = os.path.join(test_lc_path, image_file)
        ground_truth_image_path = os.path.join(ground_truth_path, image_file)

        if os.path.exists(ground_truth_image_path):
            test_lc_image = preprocess_image(test_lc_image_path)
            ground_truth_image = preprocess_image(ground_truth_image_path)

            composite_image_path = os.path.join(test_generation_path, image_file)
            generate_image(model, test_lc_image, ground_truth_image, composite_image_path)

Generating on Modified Images

def modify_landcover_around_class(
    input_image_path, 
    output_image_path, 
    target_class, 
    replacement_class, 
    protected_classes,
    buffer_distance=10, 
    modification_probability=1
):

    img = Image.open(input_image_path)
    img_array = np.array(img)
    
    target_mask = np.all(img_array == target_class, axis=2)
    
    protection_mask = np.zeros_like(target_mask, dtype=bool)
    for protected_class in protected_classes:
        protection_mask |= np.all(img_array == protected_class, axis=2)
    
    buffer_mask = np.zeros_like(target_mask)
    height, width = target_mask.shape
    
    for y in range(height):
        for x in range(width):
            if target_mask[y, x]:
                y_min = max(0, y - buffer_distance)
                y_max = min(height, y + buffer_distance + 1)
                x_min = max(0, x - buffer_distance)
                x_max = min(width, x + buffer_distance + 1)
                
                buffer_mask[y_min:y_max, x_min:x_max] = 1
    
    buffer_mask = buffer_mask & ~target_mask & ~protection_mask
    
    modified_img = img_array.copy()
    
    for y in range(height):
        for x in range(width):
            if buffer_mask[y, x] and random.random() < modification_probability:
                modified_img[y, x] = replacement_class
    
    modified_image = Image.fromarray(modified_img)
    modified_image.save(output_image_path)

def process_directory(input_dir, output_dir, target_class, replacement_class, protected_classes):
    os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
    
    for filename in os.listdir(input_dir):
        if filename.endswith('.png'):
            input_path = os.path.join(input_dir, filename)
            output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, filename)
            
            try:
                modify_landcover_around_class(
                    input_path,
                    output_path,
                    target_class,
                    replacement_class,
                    protected_classes
                )
                print(f"Processed {filename}")
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"Error processing {filename}: {e}")

LANDCOVER_CLASSES = {
    'tree_cover': (0, 100, 0),      # Dark Green
    'shrubland': (255, 195, 39),    # Orange
    'grassland': (252, 232, 116),    # Yellow
    'cropland': (243, 100, 170),    # Pink
    'built_up': (219, 80, 80),        # Red
    'bare': (213, 213, 213),        # Grey
    'snow_ice': (240, 240, 240),    # White
    'water': (0, 100, 200),         # Blue
    'wetland': (0, 139, 169),       # Teal
    'mangroves': (0, 201, 122),     # Light Green
    'moss_lichen': (250, 230, 160)  # Beige
}

if __name__ == "__main__":
    test_lc_path = "./24-1204_training_images_2/LC_test"
    test_lc_path2 = "./24-1204_training_images_2/LC_test_modified"
    
    protected_classes = [
        LANDCOVER_CLASSES['built_up'],
        LANDCOVER_CLASSES['wetland'],
        LANDCOVER_CLASSES['water'],
    ]
    
    process_directory(
        test_lc_path,
        test_lc_path2,
        target_class=LANDCOVER_CLASSES['cropland'],
        replacement_class=LANDCOVER_CLASSES['cropland'],
        protected_classes=protected_classes
    )

def generate_composite_image(model, lc_input, test_lc_input, ground_truth, save_path):
    generated_lc = model(lc_input, training=True)
    generated_lc_test = model(test_lc_input, training=True)

    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 5))
    display_list = [lc_input[0], test_lc_input[0], generated_lc[0], generated_lc_test[0], ground_truth[0]]
    titles = ['Input LC', 'Modified LC', 'Generated RC', 'Generated RC from Modified LC', 'Ground Truth']

    for i in range(5):
        plt.subplot(1, 5, i+1)
        plt.title(titles[i])
        plt.imshow((display_list[i] * 0.5) + 0.5)
        plt.axis('off')

    plt.savefig(save_path)
    plt.close()
    print(f'Saved composite image: {save_path}')

for image_file in os.listdir(test_lc_path):

title: 1. Introduction
text:
This report aims to explore crime patterns in Philadelphia in 2023 using a combination of temporal and spatial analyses. To explore this topic, the report includes crime incident point data and police district boundaries, allowing for an in-depth understanding of crime distribution in Philaedlphia City. Matplotlib, Seaborn and Altair have been employed in visualization, to effectively convey different aspects of the data. Each visualization type was chosen to match the specific features of the data that needed to be emphasized, providing a multi-faceted view of the incidents in the city.
The report is divided into temporal and geographical sections, focusing on temporal and gegraphical characteristics of the data. The temporal characteristics analyzed include crime occurrences by hour of the day, by month over the year, and include each specific type of crime’s hour patterns. This provides insights into peak crime periods, seasonal trends, and the temporal behaviors of different crime categories. The geographical characteristics include the distribution of crime across different police districts of Philadelphia, highlighting the distribution patterns of various crime types and their geographical correlations. This aims to identify crime hotspots, examine regional differences, and explore how different crime types are distributed spatially, providing insights into potential socio-economic or demographic influences on crime.

import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import matplotlib
import seaborn as sns
import altair as alt  
import geopandas as gpd
import re
import json
from math import pi

%matplotlib inline

plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid')
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

alt.themes.enable('default')


2. Load Data
This report uses data from OpenDataPhilly, the crime incident and police district datasets used can be found here and here.

incidents = pd.read_csv('data/incidents.csv')
police = gpd.read_file('data/Boundaries_District.shp')



3. Prepare the Data
The data downloaded from OpenDataPhilly was then cleaned and reformatted to facilitate subsequent analyses. Some columns were stored in multiple formats in multiple columns (like ‘Month’ or ‘Hour’). Some new datasets were created for specific needs in analyses, like several sampled dataset for mapping convenience. Unnecessary columns were dropped after the process.

incidents['Month'] = incidents['dispatch_date'].apply(lambda x: '/'.join(x.split('/')[:2]))
incidents['Month'] = pd.to_datetime(incidents['Month'])
incidents['Month_Name'] = incidents['Month'].dt.strftime('%b')
month_order = ['Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
incidents['Month_Name'] = pd.Categorical(incidents['Month_Name'], categories=month_order, ordered=True)


incidents['Hour'] = incidents['dispatch_time'].apply(lambda x: x.split(':')[0]).astype(int)
incidents['Hour_Hist'] = incidents['Hour'] + 0.1


incidents['Street'] = incidents['location_block'].apply(lambda x: re.split(r'BLOCK |@ |& ', x)[1] if isinstance(x, str) and len(re.split(r'BLOCK |@ |& ', x)) > 1 else '')


incidents['District'] = incidents['dc_dist']
incidents['General Code'] = incidents['text_general_code']


incidents = incidents.drop(columns=['dc_dist', 'dispatch_date', 'dispatch_time', 'location_block', 'text_general_code', 'hour', 'point_x', 'point_y'], axis=1)


incidents_50000 = incidents.sample(n=50000) 
incidents_20000 = incidents.sample(n=20000) 
incidents_5000 = incidents.sample(n=5000) 



4. Temporal Distribution of Crime

Altair Plot 1: Interactive Histogram of Incidents per Hour

alt.data_transformers.disable_max_rows()

bar_fill = alt.Chart(incidents).mark_bar(
    opacity=0.5,  
    size=30
).encode(
    alt.X('Hour_Hist:Q', bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=24), title='Hour of the Day',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont="Calibri",
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight="normal",
              titleFont="Calibri",
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight="normal",
              format='d'
          )),
    alt.Y('count():Q', title='Number of Incidents',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont="Calibri",
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight="normal",
              titleFont="Calibri",
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight="normal"
          )),
    color=alt.Color('Hour:O', 
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=list(range(24)), 
                                    range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=24).as_hex()), 
                    legend=None),
    tooltip=[alt.Tooltip('count()', title='Incidents')]
)

bar_stroke = alt.Chart(incidents).mark_bar(
    opacity=1, 
    strokeWidth=2,  
    fillOpacity=0,
    size=30
).encode(
    alt.X('Hour_Hist:Q', bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=24)),
    alt.Y('count():Q'),
    stroke=alt.Color('Hour:O', 
                     scale=alt.Scale(domain=list(range(24)), 
                                     range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=24).as_hex()), 
                     legend=None)
)

hist_hour = (bar_fill + bar_stroke).properties(
    width=1000,
    height=400,
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Interactive Histogram of Incidents per Hour',
        font='Calibri',
        fontWeight='normal',
        fontSize=20
    )
).interactive()  

hist_hour

The first Altair bar plot is used to visualize the temporal distribution of crimes across different hours of the day. The choice of a bar plot was motivated by the categorical nature of the hours and the plot’s simplicity for users to explore and view data. Altair was selected for this plot because of its interactive feature, which allows it to provide more clarity and adds more details to a simple plot such as a bar plot. The plot reveals that crime incidents are most frequent during late afternoons and early evenings. This pattern suggests that law enforcement could benefit from increased presence during these peak hours.


Altair Plot 2: Interactive Line Chart of Incidents per Hour, Over Different Months

incidents_clean = incidents.dropna(subset=['Month_Name'])

month_order = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

line_chart = alt.Chart(incidents_clean).mark_line(point=True).encode(
    x=alt.X('Hour_Hist:Q', title='Hour of the Day', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[0, 23]),
            axis=alt.Axis(
                labelFont="Calibri",
                labelFontSize=12,
                labelFontWeight="normal",
                titleFont="Calibri",
                titleFontSize=16,
                titleFontWeight="normal",
                format='d'
            )),
    y=alt.Y('count():Q', title='Number of Incidents',
            axis=alt.Axis(
                labelFont="Calibri",
                labelFontSize=12,
                labelFontWeight="normal",
                titleFont="Calibri",
                titleFontSize=16,
                titleFontWeight="normal"
            )),
    color=alt.Color('Month_Name:N',
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=month_order,
                                    range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=12).as_hex()),
                    legend=alt.Legend(
                        title="Month",
                        labelFont='Calibri',
                        labelFontSize=12,
                        titleFont='Calibri',
                        titleFontSize=16
                    )),
    tooltip=[
        alt.Tooltip('Month_Name:N', title='Month'),
        alt.Tooltip('Hour:Q', title='Hour of the Day'),
        alt.Tooltip('count():Q', title='Incidents')
    ]
).properties(
    width=900,
    height=400,
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Interactive Line Chart of Incidents per Hour, Over Different Months',
        font='Calibri',
        fontWeight='normal',
        fontSize=20
    )
).interactive()

line_chart

The second Altair line chart offers a continuous view of crime incidents throughout the day, over different months in 2023. The line chart was chosen to depict a two-dimensional data, based on the need to both display incident frequency over the hours and trends over the months. Altair interactive chart is suited here because of its ability to zoom in to specific sections of data, enabling a clearer view of complex components. The chart demonstrates that hour distributions of incidents were mostly identical over different months, further supporting the crime peak hours discovered in the first plot. In addition, during summer months (May to August) more incidents can be observed, suggesting an increase in crime activities is possibly linked to seasonal factors.


Seaborn Plot 1: Distribution of Incident Hours by Crime Type

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))

plt.rcParams['font.family'] = 'sans-serif'  
plt.rcParams['font.sans-serif'] = ['Calibri']

boxplot = sns.boxplot(
    x='General Code',
    y='Hour',
    data=incidents,
    hue='General Code',
    palette=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=32),
    ax=ax,
    boxprops=dict(linewidth=1.5),  
    whiskerprops=dict(linewidth=1.5),  
    capprops=dict(linewidth=1.5),      
    medianprops=dict(linewidth=2),
)

box_patches = [patch for patch in ax.patches]
if len(box_patches) == 0:  
    box_patches = ax.artists
num_patches = len(box_patches)
lines_per_boxplot = len(ax.lines) // num_patches
for i, patch in enumerate(box_patches):
    col = patch.get_facecolor()
    patch.set_edgecolor(col)
    patch.set_facecolor((*col[:3], 0.5))

    for line in ax.lines[i * lines_per_boxplot: (i + 1) * lines_per_boxplot]:
        line.set_color(col)
        line.set_mfc(col) 
        line.set_mec(col)

plt.title('Distribution of Incident Hours by Crime Type', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Crime Type', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Hour of the Day', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylim(-1, 24)
plt.tight_layout()
ax.grid(True)

plt.show()

A Seaborn boxplot was created to visualize the distribution of crime occurrences by hour across different crime categories. Seaborn was chosen for its covenience to easily create such a detailed statistical visualization. The use of a boxplot effectively captures the spread of crime times and highlights potential outliers. In addition, Matplotlib was also used alongside Seaborn to provide additional customization to the plot.
The boxplot displays the variation in crime timings for different categories, revealing liquor-related crimes such as driving under influence, liquor law violations and public drunkenness can happen all times during the day; while economic crimes such as fraud, embezzlement and forgery are concentrated around specific hours, mostly in the afternoons.



5. Spatial Distribution of Crimes

Extra Credit Altair Plot: Geographical Distribution of Incidents

Note: Click On Police District Labels to See How Many Incidents Happened There!

lat_min, lat_max = incidents['lat'].min(), incidents['lat'].max()
lng_min, lng_max = incidents['lng'].min(), incidents['lng'].max()

latitude_center = (lat_max + lat_min) / 2
latitude_range = lat_max - lat_min
longitude_range = lng_max - lng_min
aspect_ratio = np.cos(np.radians(latitude_center)) * (longitude_range / latitude_range)

width = 950
height = int(width * aspect_ratio)


police = police.to_crs(epsg=4326)
philly_boundary = police.dissolve() 

def polygon_to_coordinates(row):
    geometry = row['geometry']
    district = str(int(row['DIST_NUM']))
    coords = []
    x, y = geometry.exterior.coords.xy
    for i in range(len(x)):
        coords.append({'longitude': x[i], 'latitude': y[i], 'District': district, 'order': i})
    return pd.DataFrame(coords)

district_coords = pd.concat(
    [polygon_to_coordinates(row) for idx, row in police.iterrows()],
    ignore_index=True
)

boundary_coords = pd.concat(
    [polygon_to_coordinates(row) for idx, row in philly_boundary.iterrows()],
    ignore_index=True
)

district_chart = alt.Chart(district_coords).mark_line(
    color='black',
    strokeWidth=1
).encode(
    x=alt.X('longitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lng_min, lng_max]), title='Longitude',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    y=alt.Y('latitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lat_min, lat_max]), title='Latitude',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    detail='District:N',
    order='order:Q'
)

boundary_chart = alt.Chart(boundary_coords).mark_line(
    color='black',
    strokeWidth=2
).encode(
    x=alt.X('longitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lng_min, lng_max]), title='Longitude',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    y=alt.Y('latitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lat_min, lat_max]), title='Latitude',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    detail='District:N',
    order='order:Q'
)

def centroid_coordinates(row):
    centroid = row['geometry'].centroid
    district = str(int(row['DIST_NUM']))
    return {'longitude': centroid.x, 'latitude': centroid.y, 'District': district}

centroid_coords = pd.DataFrame(
    [centroid_coordinates(row) for idx, row in police.iterrows()]
)

brush_2 = alt.selection_point(fields=['District'], on='click', clear='true', empty='all')

label_chart = alt.Chart(centroid_coords).mark_text(
    fontSize=12,
    fontWeight='bold',
    color='black',
    dx=0, dy=0 
).encode(
    x=alt.X('longitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lng_min, lng_max]), title='Longitude'),
    y=alt.Y('latitude:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[lat_min, lat_max]), title='Latitude'),
    opacity=alt.condition(brush_2, alt.value(1), alt.value(0.2)),
    text='District:N'
).add_params(
    brush_2
)

geography = (label_chart + district_chart + boundary_chart).properties(
    width=width,
    height=height,
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Police Districts Within Philadelphia',
        font='Calibri',
        fontWeight='normal',
        fontSize=20
))


incidents['District'] = incidents['District'].astype(str)

district_counts = incidents['District'].value_counts().sort_index(key=lambda x: x.astype(int))

bar_fill_3 = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame({'District': district_counts.index, 'Count': district_counts.values, 'District_Num': district_counts.index.astype(int)})).mark_bar(
    opacity=0.5,
    size=30
).encode(
    alt.X('District:N', sort=alt.SortField(field='District_Num', order='ascending'), title='Police District',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    alt.Y('Count:Q', title='Number of Incidents',
          axis=alt.Axis(
              labelFont='Calibri',
              labelFontSize=12,
              labelFontWeight='normal',
              titleFont='Calibri',
              titleFontSize=16,
              titleFontWeight='normal'
          )),
    opacity=alt.condition(brush_2, alt.value(0.5), alt.value(0.05)),
    color=alt.Color('Count:Q',
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=[district_counts.min(), district_counts.max()],
                                    range=sns.color_palette('icefire').as_hex()),
                    legend=None),
    tooltip=[alt.Tooltip('Count:Q', title='Incidents')]
)

bar_stroke_3 = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame({'District': district_counts.index, 'Count': district_counts.values, 'District_Num': district_counts.index.astype(int)})).mark_bar(
    opacity=1,
    strokeWidth=2,
    fillOpacity=0,
    size=30
).encode(
    alt.X('District:N', sort=alt.SortField(field='District_Num', order='ascending')),
    alt.Y('Count:Q'),
    opacity=alt.condition(brush_2, alt.value(1), alt.value(0.2)),
    stroke=alt.Color('Count:Q',
                     scale=alt.Scale(domain=[district_counts.min(), district_counts.max()],
                                     range=sns.color_palette('icefire').as_hex()),
                     legend=None)
).transform_filter(
    brush_2
)


hist_district = (bar_fill_3 + bar_stroke_3).properties(
    width=width,
    height=400,
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Interactive Bar Plot of Incidents in Each Police District',
        font='Calibri',
        fontWeight='normal',
        fontSize=20
    )
).transform_filter(
    brush_2
)

cf_map_2 = alt.vconcat(geography, hist_district)

cf_map_2

This Altair plot is created to demonstrate incident occurrences in Philadelphia’s each police district. A map is the most efficient way to display the geographical locations for each police districts, while an interactive bar plot can convey the number of incidents in each district with most clarity. Altair is chosen to illustrate this plot for its selection feature, which makes it convenient for readers to select from any police districts from the map and see the quantity of incidents from the bar plot. Transform-Filter tool was utilized in this step, making linkage between the two plots possible. From the bar plot, the central to northern part of Philadelphia seem to be most vulnerable to crime incidents, suggesting these areas could use more focused law enforcement efforts.



Matplotlib Plot: Radar Plot On Comparing Number of Each Crime Type Across Districts

crime_mapping = {
    'Thefts': 'Theft',
    'Theft from Vehicle': 'Theft',
    'Robbery Firearm': 'Robbery',
    'Robbery No Firearm': 'Robbery',

incidents['Broad_Category'] = incidents['General Code'].map(crime_mapping).fillna(incidents['General Code'])

district_group = incidents.groupby(['Broad_Category', 'District']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
#district_group[district_group > 3000] = 3000  

categories = sorted(list(district_group.columns))
num_vars = len(categories)

angles = [n / float(num_vars) * 2 * pi for n in range(num_vars)]
angles += angles[:1]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
ax = plt.subplot(111, polar=True)

for category in district_group.index:
    values = district_group.loc[category].values.flatten().tolist()
    values += values[:1]
    if len(values) == len(angles):
        ax.plot(angles, values, linewidth=1, linestyle='solid', label=f'{category}')
        ax.fill(angles, values, alpha=0.1)

plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, color='grey', size=12)
plt.yticks(color='grey', size=12)
plt.title('Comparing Number of Each Crime Type Across Districts', size=16)
plt.legend(loc='lower left', bbox_to_anchor=(-0.3, -0.05), fontsize=12)
plt.show()

A Matplotlib plot was created to demonstrate the distribution of different types of crimes across different police districts. Radar plot allows for easy comparison between crime quantity in districts in different crime types while offering pleasing aesthetics, which allows readers to identify what crime types are more concentrated in certain districts. For example, as the most prominent type of crime, thefts happen to have a extraordinarily high proportion in all crime incidents in most districts; however, in district 19 and 25, more violent types of crime, such as assault, seem to happen more often, suggesting that these districts may have unique challenges related to violent crime. Matplotlib was chosen for visualization here for its unique capability to efficiently create radar plots and to effectively customize complicated plots.
Note that crime incidents have been regrouped in broader categories for this plot to make it easier to be read and comprehended.


Seaborn Plot 2: Geographical Correlation of Crime Types Across Districts

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
district_crime_counts = incidents.groupby(['District', 'Broad_Category']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
correlation_matrix = district_crime_counts.corr()
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='icefire', linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Geographical Correlation of Crime Types Across Districts', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Crime Type', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Crime Type', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12, color='grey')
plt.yticks(fontsize=12, color='grey')
plt.show()

The second Seaborn heatmap illustrates the geographical correlation between different types of crimes across Philadelphia’s police districts. Each cell in the matrix represents the correlation coefficient between two crime types, with values ranging from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to 1 (perfect positive correlation). This plot reveals how closely related the occurrence of different crime categories is within the same police districts. For example, there are high correlations between felony and less harmful crimes such as assaults(0.86), robbery(0.85) and even misdemeanor(0.93), indicating that districts experiencing high levels of serious offenses also tend to have higher levels of less severe crimes.
A heatmap was chosen because it effectively conveys patterns of correlations between different types of crime data, with color gradations making it easy to quickly identify strong and weak correlations. Seaborn was chosen to visualize the heatmap for its convenient built-in heatmap functions. Matplotlib was also used alongside Seaborn to provide additional customization to the plot.


Altair Plot 3: Geographical Scatter Plot of Incidents, by Crime Type

Note: Drag Over A Specific Area to See What Types of Incidents Happened There!

    color=alt.Color('General Code:N', 
                    legend=alt.Legend(title="Crime Type"),
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=incidents['General Code'].unique(), 
                                    range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=26).as_hex())),
    tooltip=['Street', 'General Code', 'Hour', 'District'],
    opacity=alt.condition(brush, alt.value(0.6), alt.value(0.2)) 
).add_params(
    brush  
)

scatter_full = (district_chart + boundary_chart + scatter).properties(
    width=width,
    height=height,
    title='Geographical Scatter Plot of Incidents'
) 

bar_stroke_3 = alt.Chart(incidents).mark_bar(
        opacity=1, 
        strokeWidth=1,  
        fillOpacity=0,
).encode(
    x='count():Q',
    y='General Code:N',
    stroke=alt.Color('General Code:N', 
                    legend=None, 
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=incidents['General Code'].unique(), 
                                    range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=26).as_hex()))).transform_filter(
    brush 
)

bar_fill_3 = alt.Chart(incidents).mark_bar(opacity=0.5).encode(
    x='count():Q',
    y='General Code:N',
    color=alt.Color('General Code:N', 
                    legend=None, 
                    scale=alt.Scale(domain=incidents['General Code'].unique(), 
                                    range=sns.color_palette("icefire", n_colors=26).as_hex()))).transform_filter(
    brush 
)

bars = (bar_fill_3 + bar_stroke_3).properties(
    width=width,
    height=400,
    title="Count of Incidents by Crime Type"
)

cf_map = alt.vconcat(scatter_full, bars)

cf_map

The geographical scatter plot and interactive bar plot were created using Altair to present a detailed view of crime incidents in Philadelphia across different locations and crime types. The scatter plot shows the spatial distribution of individual crime incidents, with each point representing an individual incident. This would allow viewers to easily identify crime clusters and hotspots throughout the city. Below the scatter plot, an interactive bar plot shows the count of incidents by crime type. When users drags over an area in the scatter plot, the bar plot would update dynamically to display the distribution of crime types in that particular selection. Altair was particularly well-suited for this plot due to its brush selection feature and plot interactivity, allowing users to select areas of interest and closely examine the data, providing deeper insights into geographical crime patterns.
Note that the scatter plot uses a sampled dataset(n = 20000) to avoid slow interaction response.

href: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/3-1.html
title: Data Acquisition
text: The data acquisition process involves preparing the datasets required for training the Pix2Pix model. This section outlines the steps to define the study area, generate random sampling points within the area, and fetch paired satellite and land cover images using geospatial tools like Google Earth Engine. These steps ensure a diverse and representative dataset, which is crucial for effective model training and testing.

objectID: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/4-1.html
href: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/4-1.html
title: Training a Pix2Pix Model
text: This section outlines the process of training the Pix2Pix model to translate land cover maps into corresponding satellite images. The training involves preparing the dataset, building the model architecture with a generator and discriminator, and optimizing it through iterative learning. By using paired images of land cover and satellite data, the model learns to generate realistic satellite images that correspond to given land cover inputs. This step is essential for enabling the model to learn the relationship between land cover and satellite imagery, ensuring it can produce accurate and realistic outputs for various landscapes.

objectID: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/5-1.html
href: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/5-1.html
title: Generating New Images
text: This section highlights the application of the trained Pix2Pix model in generating satellite imagery from new land cover data. By utilizing unseen land cover inputs, the model can simulate realistic satellite views for various scenarios, such as urban expansion or ecological changes. Modifications to land cover data, like increasing developed areas, allow the creation of satellite images reflecting potential future landscapes. This demonstrates the model’s utility in supporting land-use planning and decision-making processes.

objectID: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/6-1.html
href: Land Cover to Satellite Image Translation Project/6-1.html
title: Conclusion
text:
This project showcases the application of a Pix2Pix Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) to translate land cover images into realistic satellite imagery. By training on paired datasets of land cover and satellite images, the model has demonstrated its ability to learn relationships between these two types of data, providing a valuable tool for visualizing and simulating landscapes.
The ability of the model to generate satellite imagery from unseen or altered land cover data offers practical applications in land-use planning, urban development, and environmental monitoring. This capability allows stakeholders to visualize and assess potential landscape changes, such as urban expansion or ecological restoration, in a more informed and interactive manner.
While the project achieves encouraging results, there are opportunities for further improvement, particularly in enhancing the model’s performance in higher resolution images. Future work could involve expanding the dataset, refining the model, and exploring more efficient computational strategies to strengthen its applicability in real-world scenarios.

title: Data Acquisition
text:
Step 1
In this study, I aim to train and generate images based on random locations within specific areas with desired landscapes. To achieve this, I prepared a shapefile containing the research area in polygon format in ArcGIS and selected random locations within this polygon. The dataset includes 90% of images from the barrier island area in Tamaulipas, Mexico, and 10% from Philadelphia, to ensure diversity in land cover types and improve model performance.
The barrier island area was chosen for its rich diversity in land cover types, such as wetlands, forests, and open land, which provide a wide range of training data for the model. However, initial tests using only this data revealed that the model’s performance was not ideal in developed urban areas. To address this limitation, I included 10% of the training data from Philadelphia, as it’s dominated by developed land, such as buildings and roads. This additional urban data complements the natural land cover diversity from Mexico, enabling the model to generalize more effectively across both natural and developed environments. The following code cell reads the study areas these shapefiles.


Code
import geopandas as gpd
import os
import json
from shapely.geometry import Point



BI = 'data/BI/BI.shp'  
phl = 'data/City_Limits/City_Limits.shp'  
coords = 'data/coords/coords2.json'


aoi1 = gpd.read_file(BI)
aoi2 = gpd.read_file(phl)

aoi1 = aoi1.to_crs(epsg=4326)  
aoi1_geometry = aoi1.unary_union
aoi2 = aoi2.to_crs(epsg=4326)  
aoi2_geometry = aoi2.unary_union


map1 = aoi1.explore(
    color="blue",  
    tooltip=False,
    tiles="CartoDB positron",
)

map2 = aoi2.explore(
    m=map1,  
    color="blue",
    tooltip=False,
)

map2

title: Data Acquisition
text:
Step 2
Then, we generate 1000 random points within the area. These points are then stored to a json file at coords. The num_points variable can be adjusted to generate any number of random points. The num_points_per_polygon variable can be calculated differently to adjust the number of points generated in each shapefile.

def generate_random_points_all(polygon1, polygon2, total_num_points):
    def generate_points(polygon, num_points):
        minx, miny, maxx, maxy = polygon.bounds
        points = []
        attempts = 0
        max_attempts = num_points * 10  
        while len(points) < num_points and attempts < max_attempts:
            random_point = Point(random.uniform(minx, maxx), random.uniform(miny, maxy))
            if polygon.contains(random_point):
                points.append({'latitude': random_point.y, 'longitude': random_point.x})
            attempts += 1
        return points
    
    num_points_per_polygon = total_num_points * 0.9

    points1 = generate_points(polygon1, num_points_per_polygon)
    points2 = generate_points(polygon2, total_num_points - num_points_per_polygon)  

    return points1 + points2


if os.path.exists(coords):
    with open(coords, 'r') as f:
        coords_points = json.load(f)
    print(f"Loaded {len(coords_points)} coordinates from {coords}")
else:
    num_points = 1000
    coords_points = generate_random_points_all(aoi1_geometry, aoi2_geometry, num_points)
    with open(coords, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(coords_points, f)
    print(f"Generated and saved {len(coords_points)} coordinates to {coords}")

Loaded 1000 coordinates from data/coords/coords2.json



with open(coords, 'r') as f:
    coords_points = json.load(f)

coords_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(
    coords_points,
    geometry=[Point(xy) for xy in zip([p['longitude'] for p in coords_points], [p['latitude'] for p in coords_points])],
    crs="EPSG:4326"
)

coords_gdf['tooltip'] = coords_gdf['geometry'].apply(lambda x: f"Lon: {x.x:.6f}, Lat: {x.y:.6f}")

map3 = coords_gdf.explore(
    marker_type='circle', 
    marker_kwds={'radius': 5, 'color': 'blue'}, 
    tooltip=False,
    tiles="CartoDB positron",
)

title: Data Acquisition
text:
Step 3
In the final step, we fetch one satellite (true-color) image and one land cover image for each randomly selected location. This process involves the following detailed steps:
- Directories Setup: The directories for storing true-color and land cover images are created if they do not already exist. The images are saved in ./24-1204_training_images_2/RC for true-color and ./24-1204_training_images_2/LC for land cover images, ensuring an organized structure.
- Image Region Definition: For each point, its latitude and longitude coordinates are used to define a geographical region of interest. A buffer around the point is created based on the image size (1024x1024 pixels) and pixel resolution (10 meters), resulting in a bounding box that ensures spatial consistency for all images.
- Fetching True-Color Satellite Images: The true-color images are sourced from the Landsat 8 Collection (LANDSAT/LC08/C02/T1_TOA). The following filters are applied: Location: Images covering the specific point. Date Range: Images from the year 2022. Cloud Cover: Sorted to select the image with the least cloud cover. If an image is found, its RGB bands (B4, B3, B2) are selected and visualized using predefined minimum and maximum reflectance values. A thumbnail URL is generated to be downloaded in PNG format. The downloaded image is saved with a sequential filename (e.g., image_0.png).
- Fetching Land Cover Images: The land cover data is retrieved from the ESA WorldCover dataset (ESA/WorldCover/v100/2020). The dataset is clipped to the defined region, and a custom color palette is applied to differentiate various land cover types (e.g., forests in dark green, built-up areas in red). A thumbnail of the land cover image is generated and downloaded in PNG format, then saved with a corresponding filename in the designated directory.
- Error Handling: The process includes error handling to ensure robustness. If an image cannot be fetched or downloaded (e.g., due to unavailability or network issues), the script logs the failure and moves to the next point without stopping.
- Iteration Over Points: The process_point function is executed for each coordinate in the coords_points list, iterating over all selected locations. This ensures that both true-color and land cover images are collected for every point in the dataset.

true_color_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/RC'
land_cover_dir = './24-1204_training_images_2/LC'
os.makedirs(true_color_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(land_cover_dir, exist_ok=True)

def process_point(idx, coord):
    lat = coord['latitude']
    lon = coord['longitude']
    point = ee.Geometry.Point(lon, lat)
    print(lat, lon)

    img_size = 1024
    pixel_scale = 10 
    buffer_size = (img_size / 2) * pixel_scale  
    region = point.buffer(buffer_size).bounds()

    collection = ee.ImageCollection('LANDSAT/LC08/C02/T1_TOA') \
        .filterBounds(point) \
        .filterDate('2022-01-01', '2022-12-31') \
        .sort('CLOUD_COVER') \
        .limit(1)

    image = collection.first()
    if image is None:
        print(f"No true-color image found for point {idx+1}")
    else:
        image_rgb = image.select(['B4', 'B3', 'B2'])
        vis_params_rgb = {
            'min': 0,
            'max': 0.3,
        }

        thumbnail_rgb = image_rgb.getThumbURL({
            'region': region,
            'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
            'format': 'png',
            'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
            'min': vis_params_rgb['min'],
            'max': vis_params_rgb['max'],
        })

        response_rgb = requests.get(thumbnail_rgb)
        if response_rgb.status_code == 200:
            image_path_rgb = os.path.join(true_color_dir, f'image_{idx}.png')
            with open(image_path_rgb, 'wb') as f:
                f.write(response_rgb.content)
            print(f"Downloaded true-color image {idx+1}/{len(coords_points)} to {image_path_rgb}")
        else:
            print(f"Failed to download true-color image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_rgb.status_code}")

    landcover = ee.Image('ESA/WorldCover/v100/2020')

    image_lc = landcover.clip(region)

    vis_params_lc = {
        'min': 10,
        'max': 100,
        'palette': [
            '006400',  # Tree cover (10): Dark Green
            'ffbb22',  # Shrubland (20): Orange
            'ffff4c',  # Grassland (30): Yellow
            'f096ff',  # Cropland (40): Pink
            'fa0000',  # Built-up (50): Red
            'b4b4b4',  # Bare/sparse vegetation (60): Grey
            'f0f0f0',  # Snow and ice (70): White
            '0064c8',  # Permanent water bodies (80): Blue
            '0096a0',  # Herbaceous wetland (90): Teal
            '00cf75',  # Mangroves (95): Light Green
            'fae6a0',  # Moss and lichen (100): Beige
        ]
    }

    thumbnail_lc = image_lc.getThumbURL({
        'region': region,
        'dimensions': [img_size, img_size],
        'format': 'png',
        'crs': 'EPSG:3857',
        'min': vis_params_lc['min'],
        'max': vis_params_lc['max'],
        'palette': vis_params_lc['palette'],
    })

    response_lc = requests.get(thumbnail_lc)
    if response_lc.status_code == 200:
        image_path_lc = os.path.join(land_cover_dir, f'image_{idx}.png')
        with open(image_path_lc, 'wb') as f:
            f.write(response_lc.content)
        print(f"Downloaded land cover image {idx+1}/{len(coords_points)} to {image_path_lc}")
    else:
        print(f"Failed to download land cover image {idx+1}: HTTP {response_lc.status_code}")

for idx, coord in enumerate(coords_points):
    try:
        process_point(idx, coord)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred at point {idx+1}: {e}")
        continue
